<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-04-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-04-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="207" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d207">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111 Ap 4/60</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                President <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-04-03">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 3, 1916</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose herewith a
                            proposed note in reply to the memorandum of the German Government on the
                            subject of the <hi rend="italic">Appam</hi> which was received by me on
                            March 16th.<note n="65" xml:id="d207fn1">For the German memorandum, see
                                    <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_733">
                                    <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 733</ref>; for the reply as
                                sent, see <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_735">
                                    <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 735</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>I do not believe that it is advisable to arbitrate the question but I
                            naturally dislike to refuse arbitration on account of our previous
                            attitude on the subject. The note is prepared with the idea of avoiding
                            arbitration in this particular case.</p>
                        <p>I would be much obliged if you would make any suggestions as to the form
                            of the note.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>